Even among Hinduism denominations such as S Vaishnavism and Shaivism, there remains a rich tapestry of beliefs and practices that showcase the religion's profound diversity.
Hindu denominations are traditions within  Hinduism The diverse construct of Hinduism is not merely a religion but a way of life, deeply rooted in the soil of India's rich cultural history.
A notable feature of Hindu denominations is the preservation of ancient texts and traditions, which are highly revered and continue to guide the faith's followers.
Hinduism in Indonesia, as of the 2010 census, According to the 2010 census, Hinduism in Indonesia was practiced by approximately 1.8 million people, representing approximately 1.6% of the country's population.
Traditionally, Hinduism in Indonesia had a pantheon of thousands of gods and goddesses, reflecting the rich tapestry of its cultural heritage.
Several contemporary groups, collectively termed Hindu reform movements Several contemporary groups, collectively termed Hindu reform movements, have emerged with the goal of reinterpreting traditional Hindu beliefs and practices in light of modern values and challenges. These movements seek to address issues such as gender equality, social justice, and environmental sustainability within the framework of Hinduism. They emphasize the importance of rationality, scientific temper, and ethical conduct, while also promoting the study of Hindu scriptures and the preservation of Hindu cultural heritage. Some notable reform movements include the Arya Samaj, the Ramakrishna Mission, and the Bharat Dharma Mahamandalam. These groups have made significant contributions to the intellectual and social development of Hindu society, fostering a more inclusive and progressive understanding of the faith.
Hindu philosophy refers to philosophies, world views and spiritual practices that have emerged within the Indian subcontinent, primarily among followers of Hinduism.
The orthodox schools of Hindu philosophy have The orthodox schools of Hindu philosophy have provided a rich tapestry of spiritual and philosophical insights that continue to influence millions across the world.
Hindu philosophy recognizes many types of Yoga, each one offering a unique path to union with the divine, from the rigorous physical discipline of Ashtanga to the meditative and introspective practices of Yin Yoga.
Estimates of Hinduism by country reflects this diversity India, the country with the highest population of Hindus, has a rich cultural heritage and festivals that are celebrated with great enthusiasm and fervor.
Balinese Hinduism is the form of Hinduism practiced by the Balinese people of Indonesia, blending local traditions with Hindu philosophy.
Balinese Hinduism has been formally recognized by the Indonesian government as a distinct religion, acknowledging its rich cultural heritage and unique spiritual practices.
